hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a quinary face-centered cubic substitutional solution representative of a high-entropy alloy, comprising chromium (Cr), manganese (Mn), iron (Fe), cobalt (Co), and nickel (Ni), treated within the Calculation of Phase Diagrams (CALPHAD) methodology. Assume an isothermal system at temperature $T = 1600\ \text{K}$ with equiatomic composition $x_{\mathrm{Cr}} = x_{\mathrm{Mn}} = x_{\mathrm{Fe}} = x_{\mathrm{Co}} = x_{\mathrm{Ni}} = 0.2$. Use the standard substitutional solution model in which the molar Gibbs energy of the phase is the sum of:
- the reference (unary) contribution from the pure components in the same phase,
- the ideal configurational term,
- and the excess term arising from binary interactions represented by a Redlich–Kister expansion truncated at zero-th order and extrapolated to the multicomponent composition space using a symmetric scheme.

At $T = 1600\ \text{K}$, the molar Gibbs energies of the pure components in the same phase (reference states for the solution) are:
- $G_{\mathrm{Cr}}^{\circ}(T) = -21000\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$,
- $G_{\mathrm{Mn}}^{\circ}(T) = -20000\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$,
- $G_{\mathrm{Fe}}^{\circ}(T) = -20500\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$,
- $G_{\mathrm{Co}}^{\circ}(T) = -20700\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$,
- $G_{\mathrm{Ni}}^{\circ}(T) = -21500\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$.

Binary zero-th order Redlich–Kister interaction parameters are temperature dependent via $L_{ij}^{(0)}(T) = A_{ij} + B_{ij}\,T$, with the following values (all $A_{ij}$ in $\text{J mol}^{-1}$ and all $B_{ij}$ in $\text{J mol}^{-1} \text{K}^{-1}$):
- $\mathrm{Cr}$–$\mathrm{Ni}$: $A_{\mathrm{CrNi}} = 8000$, $B_{\mathrm{CrNi}} = 2.5$;
- $\mathrm{Cr}$–$\mathrm{Co}$: $A_{\mathrm{CrCo}} = 6000$, $B_{\mathrm{CrCo}} = 1.5$;
- $\mathrm{Cr}$–$\mathrm{Fe}$: $A_{\mathrm{CrFe}} = 4000$, $B_{\mathrm{CrFe}} = 1.0$;
- $\mathrm{Cr}$–$\mathrm{Mn}$: $A_{\mathrm{CrMn}} = -3000$, $B_{\mathrm{CrMn}} = -0.5$;
- $\mathrm{Ni}$–$\mathrm{Co}$: $A_{\mathrm{NiCo}} = 500$, $B_{\mathrm{NiCo}} = 0.2$;
- $\mathrm{Ni}$–$\mathrm{Fe}$: $A_{\mathrm{NiFe}} = 1000$, $B_{\mathrm{NiFe}} = 0.3$;
- $\mathrm{Ni}$–$\mathrm{Mn}$: $A_{\mathrm{NiMn}} = 2000$, $B_{\mathrm{NiMn}} = 0.2$;
- $\mathrm{Co}$–$\mathrm{Fe}$: $A_{\mathrm{CoFe}} = 700$, $B_{\mathrm{CoFe}} = 0.1$;
- $\mathrm{Co}$–$\mathrm{Mn}$: $A_{\mathrm{CoMn}} = 1500$, $B_{\mathrm{CoMn}} = 0.0$;
- $\mathrm{Fe}$–$\mathrm{Mn}$: $A_{\mathrm{FeMn}} = 1200$, $B_{\mathrm{FeMn}} = 0.1$.

Use the ideal configurational term for a substitutional solution and take the universal gas constant as $R = 8.314\ \text{J mol}^{-1} \text{K}^{-1}$.

Compute the molar Gibbs energy $G$ of the quinary solution at the stated composition and temperature, and determine which subset of binary interaction parameters $L_{ij}^{(0)}(T)$ contributes most to the excess Gibbs energy at this state. Also identify which contribution among the mixing terms (ideal configurational versus excess) dominates the mixing energetics in magnitude at $T = 1600\ \text{K}$.

Choose the single best answer that reports the numerical value of $G$ (to within about $\pm 2\times 10^{2}\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$) and correctly characterizes the dominant interaction pairs and the dominant mixing contribution:

A. $G \approx -3.91 \times 10^{4}\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$; the excess term is dominated by $\mathrm{Cr}$–$\mathrm{Ni}$ (followed by $\mathrm{Cr}$–$\mathrm{Co}$ and $\mathrm{Cr}$–$\mathrm{Fe}$), and the mixing energetics are dominated in magnitude by the ideal configurational term; for the largest pairs, $A_{ij}$ contributes more than $B_{ij}T$ at $T = 1600\ \text{K}$.

B. $G \approx -4.50 \times 10^{4}\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$; the excess term is dominated by $\mathrm{Ni}$–$\mathrm{Co}$ and $\mathrm{Ni}$–$\mathrm{Fe}$, and the mixing energetics are dominated by the unary reference term, with $B_{ij}T$ exceeding $A_{ij}$ for the largest pairs.

C. $G \approx -3.91 \times 10^{4}\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$; the excess term is dominated by attractive $\mathrm{Cr}$–$\mathrm{Mn}$ making the excess contribution negative overall, and the mixing energetics are dominated by the excess term.

D. $G \approx -3.70 \times 10^{4}\ \text{J mol}^{-1}$; the excess term is dominated by $\mathrm{Mn}$–$\mathrm{Co}$ and $\mathrm{Mn}$–$\mathrm{Ni}$, and the mixing energetics are dominated by the excess term, with $B_{ij}T$ dominating over $A_{ij}$ at $T = 1600\ \text{K}$.
